data.survey.strategy: I looked at the clues that made the most sense, and fit together.
looking for overlapped evidence
I looked for facts and worked backwards from there.
I made sure to include all potential clues even if they sounded insignificant
Looked for all information that could reasonably be tied together to form a picture.
i tried to follow the clues
common sense and leads that could be traced down

I tried to think logically about how a crime might be committed and then go from there. Then I tried to decide how unique some of the different things were, like "a handsome person" could describe a lot more people than a heavily scarred one, so it's not as likely to mean anything.
It was difficult to find my footing at the beginning. There were continually new clues added that seemed to invalidate my previous leads.
I treated things labelled evidence as true but then got confused when both the pipe cutter and blow torch were evidence.
I tried to look for clues with descriptive words that did not seem circumstantial, and then add clues that supported my theory.
Read and react to the clue and make a decision if it is relevant.
I was looking for the proper wording each time and not relying on witnesses but more on facts
I went through all the clues and tried to find common ones that led to the robber.
I tried to include everything that made sense and could solve the case.
I tried to identify clues that were most helpful in solving the case
Trying to figure out what tool was used and by whom
I tried to find the most evidence for certain items like the VW Jetta there were more clues and evidence for that car than the Honda
I tried to evaluate the clues that I felt were relevant to the case and discard the ones that didn't seem important.
I felt that any small detail could be important to solving the case.
I did my best to narrow down each clue and just used my brain.
Look at all the clues and got things down
I looked for people and things found at the scene, as well as possible motives. Extra details like age or when a car was bought didn't seem as promising
I thought about which puzzle pieces went together
I used my intelligence and logic.
Just went with what made sense to me
find things that seemed most consistent and relaible
Try to find the ones that seemed relevant.
I did my best to make a correlational between all the clues.
Connecting the most logical clues
Trying to visualize as being a real crime.
Read the information given and determine the answer based on the best facts.
Get as much information as possible
Tried to piece together various clues into a plausible story, some of them did not seem to fit
I kept looking for consistency in clue, parts of clues that were repeated. I tried to form my own narrative on how the crime was committed.
Matching clues together
I read all the clues and tried to determine what was a lead
Matching as many clues as possible
Reading the facts and determining if they sounded relevant or not.
